##Interview with Zhang Wenhong: "regarding patient zero, I only identify evidence. "

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to break through the fog, to find the truth, to watch the Times.

There are two kinds of science. One is telling you the truth

The other kind of trickery takes you into the ditch

On February 28, Zhang Wenhong, head of the medical treatment team of Shanghai Xinguan pneumonia and director of the infection department of the Mount Hua Hospital affiliated to Fudan University, was interviewed by China News Service and China News Weekly. Photo by Tom Yanjun, China News Service

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Li Peng

For more than a month, Zhang has spent most of his time "hiding" at the Shanghai Public Health Clinic, about 60 kilometers from the city center. As the head of the group of experts on the medical treatment of the newly diagnosed cases of coronary pneumonia in the designated hospital in Shanghai, the director of the infection department of the Mount Hua Hospital affiliated to Fudan University has to make rounds every day, to carefully study more than 300 confirmed cases, and has been exploring the new coronavirus "temper. ". On the 28th, in Huashan Hospital, Zhang Wenhong accepted the China news service, "China News weekly" reporter's exclusive interview.

"predicted the beginning, not the end. "

China News Week: You mentioned in the revival, China out of the darkest moment, the world seems to return to the early popular moment in Wuhan. So far, is it safe to say that a global outbreak of NCP is inevitable?

Zhang Wenhong: When Wuhan began to close down the city, I remember saying at that time that there were three possible situations in China: one was that if everything went very well, we should be able to control the epidemic in two to four months; the second was that the situation was relatively stable, in about six months or so, we got the epidemic under control; the third scenario is that China can't get it under control, and the epidemic is spreading around the world. Because that's what the United States was like during the 2009 H1N1 pandemic, which started out as a defensive effort and ended up being uncontained. So in an interview this time, the Singaporean leader said, "we are now adopting a positive prevention and control strategy, but if we can not prevent it, Singapore will accept this fact, just like the flu, and let it spread. " And then treat patients who are critically ill.

There were three outcomes for the disease that seemed daring at the time, but you knew it was right, because it was always the best, the middle or the worst. But this outbreak did appear strange phenomenon, and now China's answer paper submitted, indeed two to four months may be brought under control, but we predicted the beginning, but did not predict the outcome. At first it was thought that the world would be fine if China took control, but now it is found that China has taken control and the world is in trouble.

Now, for the first time in the world, there are more new cases worldwide than there are new cases in China, so that tells us that there are some bad signs in the world. We are also very worried that the world is spreading now that China is in control, which is a very worrying thing. At first it seemed that the world would be better off if the matter was brought under control in two to four months, but now it seems that this is not the case, leaving China and the world with many questions that need to be answered, there's a lot of hard work to be done.

Many people will ask if people from other high-incidence countries can come to you. It turns out that you are a high-incidence case. They won't let you go over there. Now, on the other hand, they have more cases. How can they do that? So all of this will make it difficult for us to control the epidemic in the future.

"regarding patient zero, I only identify evidence. "

China News Week: People say that no "patient zero" of new coronary pneumonia has yet been found, and there are reports that new coronary pneumonia may have been there long ago. There are five families of new coronary pneumonia virus in the gene family tree, and only one family in China, so does this mean that the NPV did not originate in China?

Zhang Wenhong: This is a very sensitive issue, but I always insist that there must be a definite basis. For example, where did the virus come from? Generally speaking, we look at two aspects. First, where did the virus come from, and where did it first appear? We need to track down the sequence of time. Second, we need to find its position on the evolutionary tree, the evolution of the latter gene is based on the former. So, I think that the two things should be carefully considered together, and that it should be avoided to release information when there is insufficient evidence.

After the case was confirmed in Shanghai, our team sequenced the entire genome of the Shanghai strain of the virus. Our conclusion is consistent with that of the World Health Organization. The case in Shanghai was transmitted from Wuhan, even the second generation didn't mutate when it came through. So this is the one that's popular in China this time. So you're asking me today, are there any other coronaviruses circulating in the world, where are they occurring? At what point does this data have to have very solid sequencing results and it has to be published internationally.

We are all struggling to find "patient zero, " a "patient zero" seems to be very dramatic. This is just some epidemiological evidence, and in fact what is the really important evidence about the origin of the virus? Through the whole genome sequencing, we found that the virus is genetically definitely bat coronavirus origin, and this time the virus and the coronavirus carried by bats are the same, therefore, it also caused some clinical manifestations similar to those of SARS in 2003.

Now that it is very clear that it came from the coronavirus carried by bats, did the bats come to Earth at the seafood market, or at the market in the next county, and eventually spread to the market, and then broke out in the market, does that make sense to you?

I think it's irresponsible to speculate. That's not how it works. There are two kinds of popular science, one is to tell you the real thing, and the other is to take you into the ditch. So I personally think that in the future, it should be some of China's most authoritative and trusted scientific research institutions. I think it is very important to clarify this matter, instead of allowing this random information to spread.

Otherwise, I, as an ordinary citizen, would cause me a lot of trouble. Is there something you're not telling me? So far as patient zero is concerned, I don't believe anyone, I only recognize the evidence, I only recognize the results of our own genetic sequencing.

"If you know your temper, you won't think it's very evil. "

China News Week: Many people said that the new coronavirus was "quite evil" . There are many theories about the length of the incubation period, the size of the transmission force and the confirmation of the transmission route. There are also phenomena such as the incubation period being able to spread and the recovery of Yang after recovery, is Three months too short a time to learn about a new infectious disease so far?

Zhang Wenhong: Many people now like to use the word "very evil" to describe the new coronavirus. You've been wanting to interview me for a long time, and I've been hiding out in one place, which is a treatment center in Shanghai. What was I doing hiding out there? Is to visit over 300 patients in Shanghai and make rounds every day. I have to be there as soon as I'm done here today. We have been looking at this disease, has been fumbling the new coronavirus's temper, the temper is clear, you will not think it is a very evil virus. It is, in fact, a member of the coronavirus family, albeit with a slightly different temper.

It may take a little longer to detox than you think, but who told you it only takes two weeks? Who told you that every virus detoxes at the same time? No one has said it, but you think so, so for such a virus, we think it demon, because we may not fully understand.

This time the coronavirus we saw was not as severe as the SARS virus. The World Health Organization says that one of its basic transmission numbers is between 2.0 and 2.5. The transmission intensity has already surpassed SARS, so why did it surpass SARS? The most important reason is that after SARS patients got sick, their body temperature was very high, there's also a serious condition. In this case, you might recognize it, but this new coronavirus patient has a mild disease, and if you don't recognize him in the early stages without symptoms, then it can spread at this stage, so one of its spread rates is very fast. And we also see national data, mainly aggregated transmission, which is seventy per cent, which is still very high. Such close contact transmission, is a major feature of this transmission of coronavirus, it can be said that the spread is very severe.

What are its characteristics? A bit like SARS, mainly pneumonia, also relatively heavy, but spread a bit like influenza, its characteristics between SARS and influenza, so you can only say it is a relatively personalized coronavirus.

We in China now call it COVID-19 pneumonia, the international is called it "2019 coronavirus disease" . With the deepening of the understanding of this disease, we should actually call this disease directly "2019 coronavirus disease. ". It's not just pneumonia, because many patients don't show signs of pneumonia. Without the appearance of pneumonia, you can't call it pneumonia, which is actually a coronavirus infection. In severe cases, it's not just a lung lesion, it's a heart lesion, it's a multi-organ lesion, so it's a whole disease.

"Besides, it's preventable and treatable. Do you think it's a joke? "

China Newsweek: With the expert group learning more about Covid-19, do you think it's not so terrible?

Zhang Wenhong: People think this disease is terrible, terrible because the new virus you do not know. Today, we have cured 279 patients discharged from hospital in Shanghai, a total of 337 patients, which has reached a discharge rate of 83% . The first case was confirmed in Shanghai on January 20. I went to work in the Shanghai Public Health Center on the New Year's Eve, so it was only one month. Now you see 83% of the patients have been discharged from the hospital and have been cured. So from this point of view, this disease we say today it is treatable do you agree or disagree?

At the beginning of this disease in Shanghai, the British magazine Lancet predicted that the worst situation in Shanghai would be that many people would still come in after the city of Wuhan was closed before the Spring Festival. Shanghai has the highest number of flights in China, so it put Shanghai at the top of the list. The number of people coming in from Shanghai, including the incidence rate in Wuhan, is spread by numbers between 2.0 and 2.5. If Shanghai doesn't control it, we should have 800,000 people infected. Even if you control it well, we should end up with 80,000 people infected in Shanghai. Well, now we are looking at more than 200 cases that have come in from Shanghai, and those that have been infected through contact with Wuhan. We know the epidemiological history of almost every patient in Shanghai. The cases in Shanghai were either brought in from Wuhan or came in contact with them. These two cases. There are no cases in Shanghai of the source of transmission. Basically, there are no cases at present. That is to say, all the cases that have come in or are related to them have been brought under control. 30 million people in the city, so many suspected patients, according to its mathematical model, the best result is 80,000 people infected, and now the Shanghai outbreak of 337.

From this point of view of prevention and control, China has given a very powerful model. Actually, doctors have nothing to do with prevention and control. Doctors are just treating diseases. What we doctors do is to find patients and diagnose them. This is very important for our prevention, because you can not do it without diagnosis and isolation. We're from out of town, and the 14-day home quarantine by the community is very important.

Everyone knows Singapore is doing well. Why? You come back from out of town, you come back from sick countries, you're in a home quarantine for 14 days. If you go out without a home for 14 days, you know what happens in Singapore. It's against the law. How does Shanghai do it? Shanghai depends on the cadres of our neighborhood committees, on the management of our communities, and on the consciousness of the people.

So based on today's results, do you think this disease can be prevented or not? 337 confirmed cases, 83% of them discharged in a month, and today we come back to something that's preventable and treatable, and you think that's a joke? No, it's not. And I think that as long as the whole country, as long as everyone can come together and do this as a very important thing, the disease is preventable and treatable.

The disease also spread to other parts of the world. The top countries are South Korea, Italy, Japan, and Singapore. In fact, we will compare their epidemic prevention strategies in the future, how far can we go to prevent and control this disease.

Our team will also publish an article today on our Mount Hua infected public account, comparing the epidemic prevention strategies and effects of several countries with those of our Shanghai, then this comparative result will be very important for us to formulate the strategy of Shanghai in the next step. Therefore, we say that preventable and treatable must be targeted at their own countries and regions, there is a very good strategy of prevention and control, so that we can control the epidemic situation.

China's experience does not necessarily apply to Singapore, nor does it necessarily apply to Japan, nor does its strategy apply to us. But the essential thing about the spread of infectious diseases is the same, how the source of infection is controlled, how the route of transmission is cut off, how vulnerable people are protected, and this is the same. Next, each country should develop its own prevention and control strategy according to its own national conditions and health system.

"One can not hope too much that drugs and vaccines will produce the same results as God. "

China News Week: So the disease can be prevented and treated, in fact, to a large extent, it does not depend on vaccines and drugs, but on how to prevent and control? When do you think vaccines and specific drugs will be developed? Will Not only there is no "Miracle Cure" now, there will be no "antidote" in the future?

Zhang Wenhong: Now there are many people in the vaccine and medicine, let me now to judge when it comes out, because I do not have a grasp of the first-hand materials, I think it is difficult for me to judge. But one thing is clear: As a coronavirus, we have not seen effective vaccines or drugs since the end of SARS. Mers, which is still prevalent in the Middle East, is also a coronavirus, drugs and vaccines haven't been made in years. So we can only say that it may be difficult to make drugs and vaccines. Even though we're making great progress today, if we do get the first vaccine, I think it's going to be the end of the year.

But there has to be a very clear concept, do you think that with a vaccine and a drug, you can fix the epidemic? It doesn't really look like that. Let me give you an example, which is the flu. Do you have any medicine? There are drugs and more than one, and they're effective, but do flu outbreaks happen every year? Is there a cure for everything that's contagious? It can't be solved. Is there a vaccine for flu? Is there a vaccine? Does that solve the problem? It doesn't solve the problem, so the prevention and control of infectious diseases is a systemic problem. It doesn't mean that you can solve it with a vaccine or a drug today. It depends on what kind of virus, how effective the vaccines and drugs are, and what coverage rate is, these are all questions.

A vaccine or a drug. Do you think it's important? I think it's very important. Whether it is vaccines or drugs, I think it is too late for us to solve this epidemic in China, but it will be useful for the next epidemic in other countries and regions in the world, it will be useful for us in China to face the possibility of epidemic in the future, so we should not stop the research and development of vaccines and drugs now, but we can not put all our hopes on the research and development of vaccines and drugs, at least for coronaviruses.

Different viruses have different characteristics, for example, there are some viruses you can vaccinate globally and the disease is gone, smallpox is gone, right. So this situation is different. In the short term, we still can not hope too much that drugs and vaccines will bring god-like results. We still hope that the strength of our Chinese people, we will resolutely implement our current strategy of prevention and control, consolidate the current achievements and bring the new type of coronary disease under control.

"response level down, but alertness not down. "

China News Week: We have been carrying out very intensive prevention and control for more than a month. Now some provinces have lowered the response level of epidemic prevention and control. What conditions do you think should be met? The level of prevention and control in Shanghai can be appropriately lowered?

Zhang Wenhong: Many places in China have started to reduce the level of response. The level of response has been lowered or not lowered. It involves all kinds of problems. In fact, my knowledge reserve and accumulation can not answer this question. But I can tell you clearly that Shanghai is not like other places. I am from Zhejiang, Zhejiang before the Spring Festival is very dangerous, because many people in Zhejiang go to Wuhan have come back, after the festival is out, business people went out, workers also went out, and the people who came in are not actually from Wuhan.

After the holiday, Shanghai is 15 million to 20 million input into the input, now if very hasty to reduce the response level, you have to consider a series of issues later. So I personally feel that when Shanghai will be downgraded is still a question that Shanghai can not answer on its own. I guess Shanghai is still working together with the central authorities, like Shanghai and Beijing, which are super-large cities, the economic and political importance of the city, its consideration is different from other provinces and cities.

But this does not mean that Shanghai is no longer working, does not mean that it is no longer engaged in the economy. I was stuck in traffic this morning, I couldn't get into the Yan'an Elevated Road, and I knew the city was starting to recover. The economic recovery does not mean that we are now at a lower level of preparedness or that our vigilance is going to decline. Screening in fever clinics in our hospitals is actually more intensive now than it was a while ago.

At this time, it is not good to say that the new cases in our whole city are zero. If it is zero, I am very worried. How can it be zero when so many people come in. We've found one or two or three cases in this city, and I think that's all very encouraging, I mean imported, imported cases, and the more you find, the safer our city is.

Over the next few days, the level of response will probably drop across the country, but we can't afford to lose our vigilance. Make it very clear that this is not a matter for the government, but for each and every one of you. We have to be on high alert ourselves, we have to come back from the field two weeks of self-isolation, and then go to work. In fact, do not encourage the very high density of this situation, or mask can take off. I wonder when Shanghai will take off the mask? It may be necessary to see that all the people who have returned to Shanghai, basically, have already returned to work. Then we have not found any new patients in Shanghai. I estimate that this time point is the time when we take off all the masks, well, when is it? I guess I'll have to take a look at it in the next few weeks.

"The prevention and control system in Shanghai is very good and belongs to the Shaolin School. "

China News Week: You also mentioned the concept of "management and control of Buddhism" . How should we balance "strong control" and "management and control of Buddhism" ?

Zhang Wenhong: A lot of people think Singapore is controlled by Buddhism. What is controlled by Buddhism? Singapore is now on an orange level. In fact, it does not require everyone to wear face masks, nor does it restrict community activities. In addition, I tell you, this is how I prevent and control it now. If I can prevent it, I can prevent it. If I can not prevent it, we will treat it like the flu, i'll treat the heavy patients, and you'll house-block the light ones. When you look at Singapore, you don't feel very positive. In fact, Singapore is very positive. If you look at the martial arts aspect, the current prevention and control system in Shanghai is very good. What school do we belong to? We belong to the Shaolin School, which is very clean and powerful, community protection is strong. Singapore belongs to Wudang School, you can not see it on the surface, and is very Buddhist, but it is very powerful inside.

Do you know when Singapore came under control? Singapore's been in control since January 2nd. As soon as the Chinese team arrived in Wuhan, Singapore began a comprehensive prevention and control program for Chinese aircraft. Later, visas were denied to those who came from Wuhan. When the outbreak came, it was under control very early, very early, and then very few patients came in, less than a hundred so far. A city this big, and then dozens of them come in, so it thinks the density is very low. With such a low density, if everyone wore a mask, the mask defense would be very inefficient, because you wouldn't have a chance to meet such a person. You don't get to meet people like that. You're wasting your mask. But the biggest question is, does Singapore have a mask? It doesn't have a mask, and it can't make masks. What else do you think people can wear? Singapore is to leave the mask to the doctor, the doctor to ensure. So I said a long time ago that we should leave the N95 to the doctor, but we put on the N95 mask ourselves, and we don't know why.

Singapore's strategy is to quarantine your home for 14 days after you return from a trip, and you dare to come out where the law is waiting for you. Next is the fever clinic coverage rate in Singapore, Shanghai Fever Clinic is 110, Beijing is 76, Singapore do you know how many? 800! After the outbreak, it immediately activated the community health care prevention and control system, can receive this fever patients, and then follow its process to go. Singapore is such a small place, 800 families can receive and receive heat, so you say they are Buddhist, you are joking, they are not Buddhist, it looks Buddhist, they are Wudang.

The strategy we are pursuing is in China's best interest. Prevention and control in Singapore has been very successful, so I'm going to draw a picture today, of new cases in Singapore and Shanghai, all imported, very consistent, you look exactly the same on the surface. But the martial arts they use are completely different. We use the martial arts of the Shaolin School. They use the martial arts of the Wudang School, but the results are all so beautiful. So we, Shanghai and many cities in China are also good, what do we do in the next stage? The next step is to practice internal strength. The first stage of our use of martial arts is the hard-line martial arts, the next to practice internal force, I believe that China's next stage will do very well. For one of the main reasons, I believe that the power of change in the Chinese government, in fact, can not be greater than the power of change in no other country.

"The infection department needs to be strong. Our people are safe. "

China News Week: People usually go to the hospital, as far as possible away from the Infectious Diseases Ward, now because of the epidemic, everyone's attention to infectious diseases, you as director of the Mount Hua Hospital Infection Department has the strongest infectious diseases team in China, why did you choose to study infectious diseases when you were in college?

Zhang: Don't interview me personally. I don't think it's very interesting. I just a countryman ran to Shanghai, read a book to stay to work only, you talk about infection department I tell you more. When people think infectious diseases are not important, our department is a very strong system. The earliest founder of our department was Professor Dai Ziying, a graduate of University of Oxford, who was under the tutelage of one of the inventors of penicillin. He came back and brought in the whole idea of antimicrobial therapy, of antiviral therapy, and so from that point on, our idea has been to focus on infectious, infectious diseases. Over the years, the Mount Hua Infectious Diseases Department has maintained a very strong drive for self-growth. My Mentor was Professor Weng Xinhua, a student of Dai Ziying, who in 2003 was head of the Shanghai SARS medical care expert group.

Our Department has always believed that it is virtually impossible for humans to stay away from infectious disease, because we live in nature, and nature is full of microbes that have been around a lot longer than humans, humans have been around for one million or 100,000 years since the evolution of the Great Apes, and modern humans have been around for 100,000 years, but microbes have been around for hundreds of millions of years, and they're everywhere in our environment, you can easily find a lot of microbial transspecies spread.

Some time ago, we found the swine herpes virus in meningitis patients, and then suddenly found that many places in China have this virus, how did the herpes virus in pigs get to people? And a patient from Africa, passed out, we found African trypanosomiasis, there's no medicine in China, we find the worm in 24 hours, we find the whole genome sequencing in 48 hours, and then we get the medicine from Geneva in 72 hours. It's an input disease. If you slow it down, you don't stand a chance.

In general, the COVID-19 has revealed many problems this time around. When a new development of infectious disease comes out, you have a strong ability to identify, in addition to the alarm can quickly identify this thing out. The pathogen was identified very quickly, within a week, but I mean there have been a lot of alerts, so maybe we could have done it a little earlier. So what we've been doing in our department over the years, is we've been extremely vigilant about emerging infectious diseases.

The H7N9 virus was discovered in Shanghai a few years ago, and our department was the first to detect and sequence it. We think this system is extremely important. You must have a strong ability to identify diseases in this hospital so that we can be safe, instead of pinning our hopes on the emergence of a pandemic in society as a whole, our national team will re-enter, re-conduct the identification of viruses and bacteria, and re-launch the policy of prevention and control.

China is actually doing quite well this time, but the virus is so fast that you have to get ahead of it. How to get ahead of it, personally, I think China needs ten million infectious diseases like our infectious diseases department in Mount Hua. Therefore, I urge the state to invest in our department of Infectious Diseases. In the future, we should cultivate a batch of "resident troops" and raise a batch of such people? It should be as powerful as our department. Of course, I often brag on TV, but this is also hoo-hoo. In fact, there should be a group of infection departments in China's primary hospitals that are very powerful, i think our people are safe.
